 If the players are not colluding, the the price is not equal to 60.
 Therefore, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if the regulator sees the message 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq60$
\end_inset

, then the regulator believes that firms are not colluding 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr(C,C)=0$
\end_inset

 and so regulator's payoff is 1-
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 And so the regulator best responds to the message of 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq60$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{*}=0$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if the regulator sees the message 
\begin_inset Formula $p=60$
\end_inset

, then the regulator believes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr(C,C)=1$
\end_inset

 and solves for 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{*}$
\end_inset

 s.t.:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
I^{*}=\arg\max_{I}\left\{ \sqrt{I}\left(1-I\right)+\left(1-\sqrt{I}\right)\left(-I\right)\right\} =\arg\max_{I}\left\{ \sqrt{I}-I\right\} \]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Rightarrow^{FOC}\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{\sqrt{I}}-1=0\Rightarrow I^{*}=\frac{1}{4}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

